<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-03-30T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-03-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="1018" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1018">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3416.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American
                                    Ambassador</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-03-30T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">March 30, 1912—6 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Great fear at Durango that in case Federal soldiers are withdrawn that
                            place will be at mercy of bandit bands. Request that sufficient troops
                            be retained adequately to protect Americans and American interests at
                            Durango.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>